35. A UCB may, at its discretion, implement the following illustrative best practices
observed in well-managed banks regarding Management of NPAs and may put
in place any other practices which would result in better customer service and
business development:
(1) Frame reasonably well documented loan policy and rules;
<image>
(2) Establish sound credit appraisal on well-settled banking norms;
(3) Prepare detailed and comprehensive format for credit appraisal report
for facilitating sound credit granting decisions and post disbursement
supervision and follow up;
(4) Diversify loan portfolio in terms of number of borrowers so as to avoid
concentration risk;
(5) Encourage small borrowers in view of lower credit risk and consequent
higher profitability;
(6) Adopt system of market intelligence for deciding the credibility of the
borrowers while considering loan proposals;
(7) Factor in quality of credit appraisal while giving ex-gratia incentives to
employees annually;
(8) Put in place internal credit rating system for borrowers enjoying fund
based credit facilities of ₹10 lakh and above for objective credit pricing
on an on-going basis;
(9) Review position of overdue accounts on a weekly basis to arrest
slippage of fresh accounts to NPA category;
(10) Follow up chronic NPA accounts at Head Office level directly in
addition to the efforts of the branches;
(11) Constitute a Committee at Head Office, to review irregular accounts;
(12) Obtain half-yearly balance confirmation certificates from borrowers
regularly;
(13) Emphasise reduction in Gross NPAs rather than the Net NPAs;
(14) Create separate loan review and audit department, by an independent
set of personnel to review the sanctioned loans so as to set right
irregularities observed;
(15) Create a separate 'Recovery Department' with Special Recovery
Officer appointed by the RCS;
(16) Conduct vigorous recovery drive to not allow stress assets to
accumulate;
(17) Follow-up irregular borrowal accounts vigorously;
<image>
(18) Vest one of the employees of the bank with the powers of Sales /
Recovery Officer for execution proceedings;
(19) Hold officers, on whose recommendations loans are sanctioned,
personally responsible;
(20) Start recovery efforts from the first month of default and take prompt
legal and seizure action;
(21) Scrutinize news items appearing in the newspapers for sale of property
to ascertain whether defaulters intend to dispose of property
mortgaged with the bank;
(22) Use unique ways to inform the customer that the loan is overdue, like
inviting delinquent borrowers to the branch for tea; Word the letter like
an invitation and gradually bring up the issue of non-payment of dues
when the borrower arrives;
(23) Paste sale notice / wall posters on the houses pledged as security;
(24) Undertake recovery action under 'Transfer of Properties Act' by
entrusting the work to private auctioneers;
(25) Organize employees into groups and assign each group a set of
borrowers for monitoring or recovery to pick up early warning signals
and follow them up closely; and
(26) Extend recovery competition system among staff members and
felicitate the one recovering the highest amount;
